# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-irish-sign-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australian-sign-languages] Many Australian Aboriginal cultures have or traditionally had a manually coded language, a signed counterpart of their oral language.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australian-sign-languages] There is some similarity between neighbouring groups and some contact pidgin similar to Plains Indian Sign Language in the American Great Plains.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australian-sign-languages] Sign languages appear to be most developed in areas with the most extensive speech taboos: the central desert (particularly among the Warlpiri and Warumungu), and western Cape York.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australian-sign-languages] Complex gestural systems have also been reported in the southern, central, and western desert regions, the Gulf of Carpentaria (including north-east Arnhem Land and the Tiwi Islands), some Torres Strait Islands, and the southern regions of the Fitzmaurice and Kimberley areas.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australian-sign-languages] Evidence for sign languages elsewhere is slim, but they have been noted as far south as the south coast (Jaralde Sign Language) and there are even some accounts from the first few years of the 20th century of the use of sign by people from the south west coast.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australian-sign-languages] However, many of the codes are now extinct, and very few accounts have recorded any detail.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australian-sign-languages] However, an Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander dialect of Auslan exists in Far North Queensland (extending from Yarrabah to Cape York), which is heavily influenced by the indigenous sign languages and gestural systems of the region.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australian-sign-languages] Sign languages were noted in north Queensland as early as 1908 (Roth).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australian-sign-languages] Early research into indigenous sign was done by the American linguist La Mont West, and later, in more depth, by English linguist Adam Kendon.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australian-sign-languages] Miriwoong Sign Language is also a developed or perhaps highly developed language.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australian-sign-languages] With the decline of Aboriginal oral and signed languages, an increase in communication between communities and migration of people to Cairns, the Far North Queensland Indigenous Sign Language has developed, based on mainland and Torres Strait Islander sign languages such as Umpila Sign Language.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Humans first migrated to Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, and over time formed as many as 500 linguistic and territorial groups.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people once lived across large areas of the continental shelf that were later inundated by postglacial sea-level rise at the start of the Holocene inter-glacial period, reshaping coastal landscapes and separating Tasmania from the mainland.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people maintained extensive networks within the continent and certain groups maintained relationships with Torres Strait Islanders and the Makassar people of modern-day Indonesia.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Over the millennia, Aboriginal people developed complex trade networks, inter-cultural relationships, law and religions, which make up some of the oldest continuous cultures in the world.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] At the time of European colonisation of Australia, the Aboriginal people spoke more than 250 different languages, possessed varying degrees of technology, and lived in various types of settlements.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Languages (or dialects) and language-associated groups of people are connected with stretches of territory known as "Country", with which they have a profound spiritual connection.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Aboriginal beliefs are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by later migrants, and contemporary issues.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Just over half hold secular or other spiritual beliefs or no religious affiliation; about 40% are Christian; and about 1% adhere to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared through dancing, stories, songlines, and art that collectively weave an ontology of modern daily life and ancient creation known as the Dreaming.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Studies of Aboriginal groups' genetic makeup are ongoing, but evidence suggests that they have genetic inheritance from ancient Asian peoples.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians and Papuans shared the same paleocontinent Sahul, although they became genetically distinct about 37,000 years ago.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians have a broadly shared, complex genetic history, but only in the last 200 years have they been defined by others as, and started to self-identify as, a single group.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal identity has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification, and community acceptance all of varying importance.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census shows that there were 944,171 Aboriginal people, comprising 3.7% of Australia's population.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Over 80% of Aboriginal people today speak English at home, and about 77,000 speak an Indigenous language at home.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal people, along with Torres Strait Islander people, suffer a number of severe health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Archeological evidence indicates that the ancestors of today's Aboriginal Australians first migrated to the continent 50,000 to 65,000 years ago.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] While there have been genomic studies placing arrival as late as 43,000 years ago, a 2025 study suggests that the peopling of Australia happened around 60,000 years ago, via two distinct routes.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Early human migration to Australia was achieved when it formed a part of the Sahul continent, connected to the island of New Guinea via a land bridge.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] This would have nevertheless required crossing the sea at the Wallace Line.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] It is also possible that people came by island-hopping via an island chain between Sulawesi and New Guinea, reaching North Western Australia via Timor.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] As sea levels rose, the people on the Australian mainland and nearby islands became increasingly isolated, some on Tasmania and some of the smaller offshore islands when the land was inundated at the start of the Holocene, the inter-glacial period that started about 11,700 years ago.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The modelling is based on data from archaeologists, anthropologists, ecologists, geneticists, climatologists, geomorphologists, and hydrologists.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The new models suggest that the first people may have landed in the Kimberley region in what is now Western Australia about 60,000 years ago, and had settled across the continent within 6,000 years.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians may have one of the oldest continuous cultures on earth.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] In Arnhem Land in the Northern Territory, oral histories comprising complex narratives have been passed down by Yolngu people through hundreds of generations.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The Aboriginal rock art, dated by modern techniques, shows that their culture has continued from ancient times.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Genetic studies have revealed that a population wave, termed East Eurasian Core, outgoing from the Iranian plateau during the Initial Upper Paleolithic period populated the Asia-Pacific region via a southern route dispersal.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] This wave is suggested to have expanded into the South and Southeast Asia region and subsequently diverged rapidly into the ancestors of Ancient Ancestral South Indians (AASI), Andamanese, East Asians, and Australasians, including Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians are genetically most closely related to other Oceanians, such as Papuans and Melanesians, who are collectively referred to as "Australasians," which can be described as "a deeply branching East Asian lineage".
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] This earlier group has been estimated to have possibly contributed around 2% ancestry to modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] 2017 found the bifurcation of Eastern Eurasians and Western Eurasians dates to at least 45,000 years ago, with indigenous Australians nested inside the Eastern Eurasian clade.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data on indigenous populations of Borneo and Malaysia showed them to be more closely related to other mainland Asian groups, than compared to the groups from Papua New Guinea and Australia.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] This indicates that populations in Australia were isolated for a long time from the rest of Southeast Asia.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] They remained untouched by migrations and population expansions into that area, which can be explained by the Wallace line.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The most common Y-chromosome haplogroups among Aboriginal Australians is C1b2, followed by haplogroups S and M; these latter haplogroups are also very frequent among Papuans.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] In a 2001 study, blood samples were collected from some Warlpiri people in the Northern Territory to study their genetic makeup (which is not representative of all Aboriginal peoples in Australia).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The study concluded that the Warlpiri are descended from ancient Asians whose DNA is still somewhat present in Southeastern Asian groups, although greatly diminished.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The Warlpiri DNA lacks certain information found in modern Asian genomes, and carries information not found in other genomes.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] This reinforces the idea of ancient Aboriginal isolation.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Genetic data extracted in 2011 by Morten Rasmussen et al., who took a DNA sample from an early-20th-century lock of an Aboriginal person's hair, found that the Aboriginal ancestors probably migrated through South Asia and Maritime Southeast Asia, into Australia, where they stayed.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] As a result, outside of Africa, the Aboriginal peoples have continuously occupied the same territory longer than any other human populations.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] These findings suggest that modern Aboriginal Australians are the direct descendants of the eastern wave, who left Africa up to 75,000 years ago.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Examining DNA from a finger bone excavated in Siberia, researchers concluded that the Denisovans migrated from Siberia to tropical parts of Asia and that they interbred with modern humans in Southeast Asia 44,000 years BP, before Australia separated from New Guinea approximately 11,700 years BP.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] They contributed DNA to Aboriginal Australians and to present-day New Guineans and an indigenous tribe in the Philippines known as Mamanwa.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] This study confirms Aboriginal Australians as one of the oldest living populations in the world.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] They are possibly the oldest outside Africa, and they may have the oldest continuous culture on the planet.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] A 2016 study at the University of Cambridge suggests that it was about 50,000 years ago that these peoples reached Sahul (the supercontinent consisting of present-day Australia and its islands and New Guinea).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The sea levels rose and isolated Australia about 10,000 years ago, but Aboriginal Australians and Papuans diverged from each other earlier, genetically, about 37,000 years BP, possibly because the remaining land bridge was impassable.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] This isolation makes the Aboriginal people the world's oldest culture.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The study also found evidence of an unknown hominin group, distantly related to Denisovans, with whom the Aboriginal and Papuan ancestors must have interbred, leaving a trace of about 4% in most Aboriginal Australians' genome.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] There is, however, increased genetic diversity among Aboriginal Australians based on geographical distribution.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] 2021 analysed a Holocene hunter-gatherer sample ("Leang Panninge") from South Sulawesi, which shares high amounts of genetic drift with Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] This suggests that a population split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The sample also shows genetic affinity with East Asians and the Andamanese people of South Asia.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The authors note that this hunter-gatherer sample can be modelled with ~50% Australian/Papuan-related ancestry and either with ~50% East Asian or Andamanese Onge ancestry, highlighting the deep split between Leang Panninge and Aboriginal/Papuans.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] 2021 found that Philippines Negrito people split from the common ancestor of Aboriginal Australians and Papuans before the latter two diverged from each other, but after their common ancestor diverged from the ancestor of East Asian peoples.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Like Papuans, it's believed that Aboriginal Australians underwent a secondary admixture event with Altai-related Denisovan populations after they diverged from the ancestors of East Asians, who already mixed with Denisovans.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] This event was also separate from the admixture event experienced by Filipino Negritos, explaining why Aboriginal Australians and Papuans have relatively lower Denisovan ancestry.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Based on a reevaluation of mitogenomes, Gandini et al.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] 2025 proposed a "long chronology", which suggested an earlier settlement of Sahul by two migration routes about ~60 ka.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] One route came from northern Sunda via the Philippine archipelago whilst the other came from southern Sunda via Mainland Southeast Asia, with both routes ultimately tracing back to South Asia.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The settlers that undertook these routes were ancestral to populations indigenous to Australia, New Guinea and Oceania, and were also related to other East Eurasians instead of belonging to a separate wave.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The dingo reached Australia about 4,000 years ago.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Near that time, there were changes in language (with the Pama-Nyungan language family spreading over most of the mainland), and in stone tool technology.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The first type of evidence comes from a 2013 study by the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology using large-scale genotyping data from a pool of Aboriginal Australians, New Guineans, island Southeast Asians, and Indians.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] It found that the New Guinea and Mamanwa (Philippines area) groups diverged from the Aboriginal about 36,000 years ago (there is supporting evidence that these populations are descended from migrants taking an early "southern route" out of Africa, before other groups in the area).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Also the Indian and Australian populations mixed long before European contact, with this gene flow occurring during the Holocene (c.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The researchers had two theories for this: either some Indians had contact with people in Indonesia who eventually transferred those Indian genes to Aboriginal Australians, or a group of Indians migrated from India to Australia and intermingled with the locals directly.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] However, a 2016 study in *Current Biology* by Anders Bergström et al. excluded the Y chromosome as providing evidence for recent gene flow from India into Australia.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The study authors sequenced 13 Aboriginal Australian Y chromosomes using recent advances in gene sequencing technology.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] They investigated their divergence times from Y chromosomes in other continents, including comparing the haplogroup C chromosomes.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] They found a divergence time of about 54,100 years between the Sahul C chromosome and its closest relative C5, as well as about 54,300 years between haplogroups K*/M and their closest haplogroups R and Q.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The deep divergence time of 50,000-plus years with the South Asian chromosome and "the fact that the Aboriginal Australian Cs share a more recent common ancestor with Papuan Cs" excludes any recent genetic contact.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] They attributed the disparity between their results and previous findings to improvements in technology; none of the other studies had utilised complete Y chromosome sequencing, which has the highest precision.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] For example, use of a ten Y STRs method has been shown to massively underestimate divergence times.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Bergström's 2018 doctoral thesis looking at the population of Sahul suggests that other than relatively recent admixture, the populations of the region appear to have been genetically independent from the rest of the world since their divergence about 50,000 years ago.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] He writes "There is no evidence for South Asian gene flow to Australia ....
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Aboriginal Australians possess inherited abilities to adapt to a wide range of environmental temperatures in various ways.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] A study in 1958 comparing cold adaptation in the desert-dwelling Pitjantjatjara people compared with a group of European people showed that the cooling adaptation of the Aboriginal group differed from that of the Europeans, and that they were able to sleep more soundly through a cold desert night.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] A 2014 Cambridge University study found that a beneficial mutation in two genes that regulate thyroxine, a hormone involved in regulating body metabolism, helps to regulate body temperature in response to fever.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The effect of this is that the desert people are able to have a higher body temperature without accelerating the activity of the whole of the body, which can be especially detrimental in childhood diseases.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] This helps protect people to survive the side-effects of infection.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that the Indigenous Australian population at the time of first European settlement numbered at least 314,500 people.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Based on the 2021 census, the Australian Bureau of Statistics estimates there were 901,655 Aboriginal Australians, and 42,516 who identified as both Aboriginal Australian and Torres Strait Islander.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] These groups comprise 3.7% of the total Australian population.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] 39,538 people identified as Torres Strait Islander, which is a different ethnic group from Aboriginal Australian.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Based on initial 2021 census counts, the Aboriginal and Torres Strait islander population grew 25.2%, since the previous census in 2016.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Demographic factors – births, deaths and migration – accounted for 43.5% of the increase (71,086 people).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] In turn, 76.2% of that increase was attributed to people aged 0–19 years in 2021, broken down as 52.5% for 0–4 year olds (births since 2016) and 23.7% for 5–19 year olds.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Reasons for the increase in Aboriginal population also include non-demographic factors.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] These include changes in individuals' identification as Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander in different censuses, and individuals completing a census form in 2021 but not in 2016.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] These factors accounted for 56.5% of the increase in the Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander population.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous Australians (including Torres Strait Islanders) are less likely to live in the major Australian cities than are non-Indigenous Australians (41% compared with 73%).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Although humans arrived in Australia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, it is possible that the ancestor language of existing Aboriginal languages is as recent as 12,000 years old.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Over 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 84% of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders spoke only English at home.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018-19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use are endangered.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] According to the 2021 census, the classifiable Aboriginal languages with the most speakers are Kriol (7,403), Djambarrpuyngu (3,839), Pitjantjatjara (3,399), Warlpiri (2,592), Murrinh Patha (2,063) and Tiwi (2,053).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] There were also over 10,000 people who spoke an Indigenous language that could not be further defined or classified.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] A number of English-based creoles have arisen in Australia after European contact, of which Kriol is among the strongest and fastest-growing Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Kriol is spoken in the Northern Territory and Western Australia.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] It is estimated that there are 20,000 to 30,000 speakers of Indigenous creole languages.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Before British colonisation, there were perhaps five to sixteen languages on Tasmania, possibly related to one another in four language families.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The last speaker of a traditional Tasmanian language, Fanny Cochrane Smith, died in 1905.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Palawa kani is an in-progress constructed language, built from a composite of surviving words from various Tasmanian Aboriginal languages.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Traditional Indigenous languages often incorporated sign systems to aid communication with the hearing impaired, to complement verbal communication, and to replace verbal communication when the spoken language was forbidden for cultural reasons.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Many of these sign systems are still in use.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Dispersing across the Australian continent over time, the ancient people expanded and differentiated into distinct groups, each with its own language and culture.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] More than 400 distinct Australian Aboriginal peoples have been identified, distinguished by names designating their ancestral languages, dialects, or distinctive speech patterns.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] According to noted anthropologist, archaeologist and sociologist Harry Lourandos, historically, these groups lived in three main cultural areas, the Northern, Southern and Central cultural areas.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The Northern and Southern areas, having richer natural marine and woodland resources, were more densely populated than the Central area.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Other group names are based on the language group or specific dialect spoken.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] These also coincide with geographical regions of varying sizes.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] However, these lists are neither exhaustive nor definitive, and there are overlaps.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Different approaches have been taken by non-Aboriginal scholars in trying to understand and define Aboriginal culture and societies, some focusing on the micro-level (tribe, clan, etc.), and others on shared languages and cultural practices spread over large regions defined by ecological factors.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Anthropologists have encountered many difficulties in trying to define what constitutes an Aboriginal people/community/group/tribe, let alone naming them.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Knowledge of pre-colonial Aboriginal cultures and societal groupings is still largely dependent on the observers' interpretations, which were filtered through colonial ways of viewing societies.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Some Aboriginal peoples identify as one of several saltwater, freshwater, rainforest or desert peoples.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The term *Aboriginal Australians* includes many distinct peoples who have developed across Australia for over 50,000 years.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] These peoples have a broadly shared, complex, genetic history, but it is only in the last two hundred years that they have been defined and have started to self-identify as a single group socio-politically.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] While some preferred the term *Aborigine* to *Aboriginal* in the past, as the latter was seen to have more directly discriminatory legal origins, use of the term *Aborigine* has declined in recent decades, as many consider the term an offensive and racist hangover from Australia's colonial era.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The definition of the term *Aboriginal* has changed over time and place, with family lineage, self-identification and community acceptance all being of varying importance.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The term *Indigenous Australians* refers to Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islander peoples, and the term is conventionally only used when both groups are included in the topic being addressed, or by self-identification by a person as Indigenous.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] As of 2021, 51% of Indigenous people stated that they held a secular or other spiritual belief or no religious affiliation; 41% were affiliated to Christianity; and 1% were affiliated to a traditional Aboriginal religion.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Australian Indigenous people have beliefs unique to each mob (tribe) and have a strong connection to the land.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Contemporary Indigenous Australian beliefs are a complex mixture, varying by region and individual across the continent.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] They are shaped by traditional beliefs, the disruption of colonisation, religions brought to the continent by Europeans, and contemporary issues.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Traditional cultural beliefs are passed down and shared by dancing, stories, songlines and art—especially Papunya Tula (dot painting)—collectively telling the story of creation known as The Dreamtime.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Additionally, traditional healers were also custodians of important Dreaming stories as well as their medical roles (for example the Ngangkari in the Western desert).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Some core structures and themes are shared across the continent with details and additional elements varying between language and cultural groups.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] For example, in The Dreamtime of most regions, a spirit creates the earth then tells the humans to treat the animals and the earth in a way that is respectful to land.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] In Northern Territory this spirit is commonly said to be a huge snake or snakes that weaved its way through the earth and sky making the mountains and oceans.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] But in other places the spirits who created the world are known as wandjina rain and water spirits.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Major ancestral spirits include the Rainbow Serpent, Baiame, Dirawong and Bunjil.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, the Arrernte people of central Australia believed that humanity originated from great superhuman ancestors who brought the sun, wind and rain as a result of breaking through the surface of the Earth when waking from their slumber.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Many Dreamtime stories are still believed by many Indigenous Australians to this day.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Taken as a whole, Aboriginal Australians, along with Torres Strait Islander people, have a number of health and economic deprivations in comparison with the wider Australian community.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Due to the aforementioned disadvantage, Aboriginal Australian communities experience a higher rate of suicide, as compared to non-indigenous communities.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] These issues stem from a variety of different causes unique to indigenous communities, such as historical trauma, socioeconomic disadvantage, and decreased access to education and health care.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Also, this problem largely affects indigenous youth, as many indigenous youth may feel disconnected from their culture.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] To combat the increased suicide rate, many researchers have suggested that the inclusion of more cultural aspects into suicide prevention programs would help to combat mental health issues within the community.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Past studies have found that many indigenous leaders and community members, do in fact, want more culturally-aware health care programs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Similarly, culturally-relative programs targeting indigenous youth have actively challenged suicide ideation among younger indigenous populations, with many social and emotional wellbeing programs using cultural information to provide coping mechanisms and improving mental health.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] Indigenous communities in remote Australia are often small, isolated towns with basic facilities, on traditionally owned land.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] These communities have between 20 and 300 inhabitants and are often closed to outsiders for cultural reasons.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aboriginal-australians] The long-term viability and resilience of Aboriginal communities in desert areas has been discussed by scholars and policy-makers.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] For over a decade, the deaf children of the village have attended a boarding school in Mampong-Akuapem, where the ASL based Ghanaian Sign Language is used.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As a consequence, this language has become the first language of these children and their command of AdaSL is decreasing.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This is likely to lead to a complete shift of the deaf community in Adamorobe to Ghanaian Sign Language.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As such, AdaSL is an endangered sign language.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe is situated approximately 30 to 40 kilometers north of Accra in the Akuapem Hills.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] It is a predominantly Akan village, with the majority of the population speaking the Akan language (Akuapem Twi) in addition to using AdaSL.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The community gained attention for its unusually high incidence of hereditary deafness, a phenomenon that has shaped the village's cultural and linguistic landscape.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other deaf communities where deaf individuals are socially marginalized, Adamorobe's deaf residents are fully integrated into village life.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Hearing villagers commonly use AdaSL in daily interactions, creating a bilingual environment that bridges the hearing and deaf worlds seamlessly.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL shares signs and prosodic features with some other sign languages in the region, such as Bura Sign Language, but it has been suggested these similarities are due to culturally shared gestures rather than a genetic relationship.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL has features that set it apart from the sign languages of large deaf communities studied so far, including the absence of the type of classifier construction that expresses motion or location (sometimes called "entity classifiers").
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, AdaSL uses several types of serial verb constructions also found in the surrounding spoken language, Akan.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Nancy Frishberg suggests that AdaSL may be related to the "gestural trade jargon used in the markets throughout West Africa".
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe Sign Language possesses distinct grammatical structures and vocabulary that set it apart from Ghanaian Sign Language and other national or international sign languages.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many urban sign languages that develop within educational institutions, AdaSL evolved organically within a close-knit community, resulting in unique syntactic constructions and simultaneous sign formations.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Its use is characterized by spatial grammar, classifier constructions, and gestures deeply embedded in the local culture.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The language is not mutually intelligible with GSL, and many signs are specific to Adamorobe's cultural context, making it a rich subject of linguistic study.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL also exhibits a lower reliance on fingerspelling compared to GSL, and it preserves several features that are considered archaic or absent in more standardized sign languages.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf culture in Adamorobe is notably inclusive.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf residents have historically participated fully in social, economic, and cultural activities.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other societies, deafness in Adamorobe does not carry a stigma.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, sign language has been a natural and respected form of communication, used not only by deaf individuals but also by hearing family members, friends, and neighbors.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This integration is evident in communal gatherings, marketplaces, and traditional ceremonies where sign language is used openly.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The social fabric of Adamorobe has long celebrated this coexistence, which has contributed to the resilience of its deaf community despite external pressures.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL is believed to have emerged over 200 years ago, alongside the settlement's founding.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Genetic studies suggest that the high incidence of deafness in Adamorobe is due to a hereditary mutation passed down through generations.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The earliest academic references to Adamorobe and its sign language date back to the mid-20th century, with researchers noting the community's unique integration of deaf individuals.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] In the 1960s and 1980s, the introduction of formal deaf education in Ghana led to the exposure of Adamorobe's deaf children to Ghanaian Sign Language, which is derived from American Sign Language (ASL).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This exposure began to shift the linguistic practices of younger generations, who now tend to use GSL more frequently than AdaSL.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] A critical turning point in the village's history came in 1975 when the local chief instituted a ban on marriages between deaf individuals in an effort to reduce the incidence of hereditary deafness.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] While this policy effectively decreased the number of deaf births, it also inadvertently threatened the long-term survival of AdaSL.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Today, Adamorobe Sign Language faces significant challenges.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The number of deaf individuals in the village has declined due to the marriage policy that discouraged unions between deaf people.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Additionally, the younger generation of deaf children is increasingly adopting Ghanaian Sign Language through formal education, which reduces the intergenerational transmission of AdaSL.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The influence of urbanization and national language policies further accelerates the shift away from village sign languages.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Without deliberate preservation efforts, AdaSL risks becoming endangered or possibly extinct within the next few decades.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Several linguists and anthropologists have documented Adamorobe Sign Language extensively in recent years.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Their efforts aim to preserve the language's unique features and raise awareness of its cultural importance.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] However, there are limited formal initiatives within the village to revitalize or maintain AdaSL among younger generations.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Potential preservation strategies include community-based language programs, the development of AdaSL teaching materials, and the integration of the language into local schools.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Encouraging the use of AdaSL in social and cultural events could also contribute to its sustainability.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Education for the deaf in Afghanistan grew out of educational efforts among Afghan refugees in Peshawar in the 1990s, making Pakistani Sign Language (IPSL) an early influence on Afghan Sign Language.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The first formal school for the deaf in Afghanistan was established in Jalalabad in 1995 by SERVE Afghanistan.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] That same year, SERVE began a project to document Afghan Sign Language, and later produced a trilingual (Dari, Pashto, and English) dictionary of Afghan Sign Language.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The language derives from the Deaf-community sign language of Jalalabad, and it is not known what connection it may have, if any, with the sign languages of other cities with established deaf populations, which are principally Mazar-i-Sharif, Herat, and Kandahar.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Early analysis suggested some AFSL signs may have come from Pakistani Sign Language (IPSL) or American Sign Language (ASL), although intensive research on this link was not undertaken at the time.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] While IPSL's influence would have been due to regional exchange, ASL could have had an influence due to its use by some SERVE teachers in its early programming.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Fingerspelling was introduced to AFSL in the late 1990s, after SERVE educators visited the Holy Land Institute for the Deaf in Jordan.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Thus, Jordanian Sign Language and AFSL share a fingerspelling alphabet, although AFSL also introduced some additional letters to represent letters not found in the Arabic script.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Afghan Sign Language is primarily spoken in Jalalabad and Kabul, which have three large schools for the deaf between them.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] Smaller deaf populations who use AFSL are also found in major urban centers in the country, those being Mazar-e Sharif, Herat, and Kandahar.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/afghan-sign-language] The majority of profoundly deaf Afghans (estimated at 30,000 in 2013) have never attended a school for the deaf.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] American Sign Language (ASL) has grammar just like any other sign language or spoken language.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The study of ASL structure dates back to William Stokoe, Dorothy Casterline, and Carl Croneberg in the 1960s.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Since then, linguists have been describing patterns in ASL responsible for creating meaning at all kinds of levels, from the word, to phrases and sentences and beyond.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all of these linguists ascribe to the same theoretical framework, using various theories, models, and analyses.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some analyze the language from a generative linguistics perspective, while others from a cognitive linguistics perspective.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL morphology, publications have historically categorized morphological processes under two umbrellas: derivational morphology and inflectional morphology.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Derivational morphology is the process by which new units can be created in a language, and like any other language, this process has been observed in a variety of forms in ASL.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One form of derivational morphology occurs when a change in movement changes the sign's meaning – often between a noun and a verb.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This may be done either by reduplicating the movement of the verb if the verb has a single movement, or by restraining (making smaller and faster) the movement of the verb if it already has repeated movement.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the noun CHAIR is derived from the verb SIT through reduplication.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way of deriving new words in ASL is via the process of compounding, which often differ in meaning from their constituent signs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the signs FACE and STRONG compound to create a new sign FACE^STRONG, meaning 'to resemble'.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed various compounds as a type of suffixation.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Agent nouns may be derived from verbs by adding the sign, or suffix, AGENT and deleting the final hold of the verb, e.g.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Superlatives have also been analyzed as created by a formed by suffixation, e.g.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, Ted Supalla's work on ASL verbs of motion analyzed these signs as consisting of many different affixes, articulated simultaneously according to complex grammatical constraints.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This differs from the concatenative morphology of many spoken languages, which except for suprasegmental features, such as tone, are tightly constrained by the sequential nature of voice sounds.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation is another derivational morphological process that has been studied in ASL.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Certain types of signs, for example, those relating to time and age, may incorporate numbers by assimilating their handshape.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the word for 'week' has handshape /B/ with the weak hand and /1/ with the active hand; the active hand's handshape may be changed to the handshape of any number up to 9 to indicate that many weeks.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed this phenomenon as a type of affixation.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Signs of age, for example, will begin with a touch at the chin.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They argue that this touch functions as a prefix which completely assimilates with the handshape of the corresponding age number.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For instance, the word for 'nine' is signed with an /F/ handshape produced ipsilaterally in front of the signer's shoulder.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The chin-touch in 'nine years old' can be analyzed as an affix, which is then produced with this same /F/ handshape.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'three years old', however, the prefix is made with a 3 handshape.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Inflectional morphology adds units of language to other words.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, this would be changing 'watch' to 'watches' or 'watching.' In ASL, the sign may remain unchanged as WATCH, or the meaning may change based on non-manual markers (NMM).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL morphology demonstrates reduplication and indexicality as well.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are about 20 non-manual modifiers in ASL, which are either adjectival or adverbial.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rather than relying on sequential affixes, ASL makes heavy use of simultaneous modification of signs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One example of this is found in the aspectual system (see below); another is *numeral incorporation:* There are several families of two-handed signs which require one of the hands to take the handshape of a numeral.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, drawing the dominant hand lengthwise across the palm and fingers of a flat B hand indicates a number of weeks; the dominant hand takes the form of a numeral from one to nine to specify how many weeks.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are analogous signs for 'weeks ago' and 'weeks from now', etc., though in practice several of these signs are only found with the lower numerals.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL also has a system of classifiers which may be incorporated into signs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These classifiers are moved through sign space to iconically represent the actions of their referents.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, an ILY hand may 'lift off' or 'land on' a horizontal B hand to sign an aircraft taking off or landing; a 3 hand may be brought down on a B hand to sign parking a car; and a G hand may be brought toward a V hand to represent one person approaching two.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The frequency of classifier use depends greatly on genre, occurring at a rate of 17.7% in narratives but only 1.1% in casual speech and 0.9% in formal speech.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Frames are a morphological device that may be unique to sign languages (Liddell 2004).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are incomplete sets of the features which make up signs, and they combine with existing signs, absorbing features from them to form a derived sign.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is the frame which specifies the number and nature of segments in the resulting sign, while the basic signs it combines with lose all but one or two of their original features.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One, the WEEKLY frame, consists of a simple downward movement.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It combines with the signs for the days of the week, which then lose their inherent movement.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'Monday' consists of an M/O hand made with a circling movement.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'MondayWEEKLY' (that is, 'on Mondays') is therefore signed as an M/O hand that drops downward, but without the circling movement.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A similar ALL DAY frame (a sideward pan) combines with times of the day, such as 'morning' and 'afternoon', which likewise keep their handshape and location but lose their original movement.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation (see above) also uses frames.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, in ASL frames are most productively utilized for verbal aspect.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] While there is no grammatical tense in ASL, there are numerous verbal aspects.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are produced by modulating the verb: through reduplication, by placing the verb in an aspectual frame (see above), or with a combination of these means.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] An example of an aspectual frame is the *unrealized inceptive* aspect ('just about to X'), illustrated here with the verb 'to tell'.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'To tell' is an indexical (directional) verb, where the index finger (a G hand) begins with a touch to the chin and then moves outward to point out the recipient of the telling.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The handshape throughout the sign is whichever is required by the final hold, in this case a G hand.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The variety of aspects in ASL can be illustrated by the verb 'to be sick', which involves the middle finger of the Y/8 hand touching the forehead, and which can be modified by a large number of frames.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Several of these involve reduplication, which may but need not be analyzed as part of the frame.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These modulations readily combine with each other to create yet finer distinctions.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all verbs take all aspects, and the forms they do take will not necessarily be completely analogous to the verb illustrated here.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Conversely, not all aspects are possible with this one verb.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect is unusual in ASL in that transitive verbs derived for aspect lose their transitivity.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Reduplication is also used for expressing verbal number.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Verbal number indicates that the action of the verb is repeated; in the case of ASL it is apparently limited to transitive verbs, where the motion of the verb is either extended or repeated to cover multiple object or recipient loci.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] (Simple plurality of action can also be conveyed with reduplication, but without indexing any object loci; in fact, such aspectual forms do not allow objects, as noted above.) There are specific dual forms (and for some signers trial forms), as well as plurals.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the singular verb uses reduplication, that is lost in the dual and plural forms.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of personal name signs in ASL: fingerspelled, arbitrary, and descriptive.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Fingerspelled names are simply spelled out letter-by-letter.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs only refer to a person's name, while descriptive name signs refer to a person's personality or physical characteristics.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Once given, names are for life, apart from changing from one of the latter types to an arbitrary sign in childhood.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are usually assigned by another member of the Deaf community, and signal inclusion in that community.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are not used to address people, as names are in English, but are used only for third-person reference, and usually only when the person is absent.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The majority of people, probably well in excess of 90%, have arbitrary name signs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are initialized signs: The handshape is the initial of one of the English names of the person, usually the first.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign may occur in neutral space, with a tremble; with a double-tap (as a noun) at one of a limited number of specific locations, such as the side of the chin, the temple, or the elbow; or moving across a location or between two locations, with a single tap at each.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Single-location signs are simpler in connotation, like English "Vee"; double-location signs are fancier, like English "Veronica".
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sam Supalla (1992) collected 525 simple arbitrary name signs like these.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two constraints on arbitrary signs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, it should not duplicate an existing ASL word.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Second, there should not be more than one person with the name sign in the local community.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person moves to a new community where someone already has their name sign, then the newcomer is obligated to modify theirs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is usually accomplished by compounding the handshape, so that the first tap of the sign takes the initial of the person's first English name, and the second tap takes the initial of their last name.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are potentially thousands of such compound-initial signs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs are not initialized, but rather use non-core ASL signs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They tend to be assigned and used by children, rather like "Blinky" in English.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Parents do not give such names to their children, but most Deaf people do not have deaf parents and are assigned their name sign by classmates in their first school for the deaf.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] At most 10% of Deaf people retain such name signs into adulthood..
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs became established very early in the history of ASL.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs refer to a person's appearance or personality.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The two systems, arbitrary and descriptive, are sometimes combined, usually for humorous purposes.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Hearing people learning ASL are also often assigned combined name signs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is not traditional for Deaf people.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sometimes people with very short English names, such as "Ann" or "Lee", or ones that flow easily, such as "Larry", may never acquire a name sign, but may instead be referred to with finger-spelling.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-Manual Markers (NMM), or Non-Manual Signals (NMS) are communication methods not found in the hands.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They typically consist of facial expressions and body language.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs can change the grammar of a sentence.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not every sign uses non-manual markers, but for many others, these markers determine what sign is being produced.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some examples of non-manual markers would be the shifting of shoulders, the lowering or raising of eyebrows, a head nod or shake, scrunching of the nose, pursing of the lips, or an open mouth.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs are important for indicating if a question is being asked.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For *WH-* questions, the eyebrows are lowered, and for *YES/NO* questions, the eyebrows are raised.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is hard to indicate if a question is being asked otherwise without facial indicators.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another example would be between *I UNDERSTAND* and *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign for this is the same; the hand is held up near the forehead with the palm facing the self.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the person is nodding and has their eyebrows raised, it means *I UNDERSTAND*.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If they are shaking their head with eyebrows lowered, it means *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Understanding ASL grammar requires understanding the difference between a signer's dominant and non-dominant hand.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person is right-handed, then their right hand is their dominant hand, and their left hand is their non-dominant hand.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Almost all signs are completed with the more active, dominant hand, while the non-dominant hand serves as a base.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For signs requiring two hands, the dominant hand performs more of the active component.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a subject–verb–object (SVO) language.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, OSV is also an accepted sentence form.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The default SVO word order is sometimes altered by processes including topicalization and null elements.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is marked either with non-manual signals like eyebrow or body position, or with prosodic marking such as pausing.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These non-manual grammatical markings (such as eyebrow movement or head-shaking) may optionally spread over the c-command domain of the node which it is attached to.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, ASL is a pro-drop language, and when the manual sign that a non-manual grammatical marking is attached to is omitted, the non-manual marking obligatorily spreads over the c-command domain.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The full sentence structure in ASL is [topic] [subject] verb [object] [subject–pronoun–tag].
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics and *tags* are both indicated with non-manual features, and both give a great deal of flexibility to ASL word order.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within a noun phrase, the word order is noun–number and noun–adjective.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL does not have a copula (linking 'to be' verb).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition to its basic topic–comment structure, ASL typically places an adjective after a noun, though it may occur before the noun for stylistic purposes.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numerals also occur after the noun, a very rare pattern among oral languages.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Adverbs, however, occur before the verbs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Most of the time adverbs are simply the same sign as an adjective, distinguished by the context of the sentence.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] When the scope of the adverb is the entire clause, as in the case of time, it comes before the topic.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL makes heavy use of time-sequenced ordering, meaning that events are signed in the order in which they occur.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, for *I was late to class last night because my boss handed me a huge stack of work after lunch yesterday,* one would sign 'YESTERDAY LUNCH FINISH, BOSS GIVE-me WORK BIG-STACK, NIGHT CLASS LATE-me'.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In stories, however, ordering is malleable, since one can choose to sequence the events either in the order in which they occurred or in the order in which one found out about them.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has been claimed that tense in ASL is marked adverbially, and that ASL lacks a separate category of tense markers.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] (1992, 1995) argue that "Tense" (T) is indeed a distinct category of syntactic head, and that the T node can be occupied either by a modal (e.g.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect may be marked either by verbal inflection or by separate lexical items.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As noted above, in ASL aspectually marked verbs cannot take objects.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] To deal with this, the object must be known from context so that it does not need to be further specified.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It may be used as the topic of the utterance at hand.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Of these two strategies, the first is the more common.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic sets off background information that will be discussed in the following main clause.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topicalization is used productively in ASL and often results in surface forms that do not follow the basic SVO word order.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In order to non-manually mark topics, the eyebrows are raised and the head is tilted back during the production of a topic.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The head is often lowered toward the end of the sign, and sometimes the sign is followed rapidly nodding the head.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way topics may be signed is by shifting the body.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The signer may use the space on one side of his/her body to sign the topic, and then shifts to the other side for the rest of the sentence.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL utterances do not require topics, but their use is extremely common.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are used for purposes of information flow, to set up referent loci (see above), and to supply objects for verbs which are grammatically prevented from taking objects themselves (see below).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, people tend to want to set up the object of their concern first and then discuss what happened to it.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of non-manual topic markers, all of which involve raised eyebrows.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The three types of non-manual topic markers are used with different types of topics and in different contexts, and the topic markings cannot spread over other elements in the utterance.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics can be moved from and remain null in the main clause of an utterance, or topics can be base-generated and either be co-referential to either the subject or object in the main clause or be related to the subject of object by a semantic property.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The first type of non-manual marking, topic marking 1 (tm1), is only used with a moved topic.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm1 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and head tilted backwards.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] At the end of the sign the head moves down and there is a pause, often with an eye blink, before the sentence is continued.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topic marking 2 (tm2) and topic marking 3 (tm3) are both used with base-generated topics.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and the head tilted backwards and to the side.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Toward the end of the sign the head moves forward and to the opposite side, and there is a pause and often an eye blink before continuing.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For tm3 the eyebrows are raised and the eyes are opened wide, the head starts tilted down and jerks up and down, the lips are opened and raised, and the head is nodded rapidly a few times before pausing and continuing the sentence.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Although both tm2 and tm3 accompany base-generated topics, they are used in different contexts.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is used to introduce new information and change the topic of a conversation to something that the signer is going to subsequently characterize, while tm3 is used to introduce new information that the signer believes is already known by his/her interlocutor.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 may be used with any base-generated topic, whereas only topics that are co-referential with an argument in the sentence may be marked with tm3.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL sentences may have up to two marked topics.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Possible combinations of topic types are two tm2 topics, two tm3 topics, tm2 preceding tm1, tm3 preceding tm1, and tm2 preceding tm3.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sentences with these topic combinations in the opposite orders or with two tm1 topics are considered ungrammatical by native signers.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Relative clauses are signaled by tilting back the head and raising the eyebrows and upper lip.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is done during the performance of the entire clause.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] where the brackets here indicate the duration of the non-manual features.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the sign 'recently' were made without these features, it would lie outside the relative clause, and the meaning would change to "the dog which chased the cat recently came home".
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Negated clauses may be signaled by shaking the head during the entire clause.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic, however, cannot be so negated; the headshake can only be produced during the production of the main clause.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, in many communities, negation is put at the end of the clause, unless there is a wh- question word.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the sentence, "I thought the movie was not good," could be signed as, "BEFORE MOVIE ME SEE, THINK WHAT?
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two manual signs that negate a sentence, NOT and NONE, which are accompanied by a shake of the head.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of questions with different constructions in ASL: wh- questions, yes/no questions, and rhetorical questions.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are grammatical and semantic features that do not include the use of hands.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They can include mouth shape, eye gazes, facial expressions, body shifting, head tilting, and eyebrow raising.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings can also aid in identifying sentence type, which is especially relevant to our discussion of different types of interrogatives.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Wh-questions can be formed in a variety of ways in ASL.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The wh-word can appear solely at the end of the sentence, solely at the beginning of the sentence, at both the beginning and end of the sentence (see section 4.4.2.1 on 'double-occurring wh-words', or in situ (i.e. where the wh-word is in the sentence structure before movement occurs)).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Manual wh-signs are also accompanied by a non-manual grammatical marking (see section 4.4.1), which can include a variety of features.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This non-manual grammatical marking can spread optionally over the entire wh-phrase or just a small part.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some languages have very few wh-words, where context and discourse are sufficient to elicit the information that one needs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL has many different wh-words, with certain wh-words having multiple variations.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] A list of the wh-words of ASL can be found below.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As mentioned above, ASL possesses wh-questions with word initial placement, word final placement, in situ structure, but the most unique style of wh-word occurrence in ASL is where the wh-word occurs twice, copied in final position.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling can be seen in the table below.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling provides a useful template to analyze two separate analyses about whether wh-words move rightward or leftward in ASL.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] While some researchers argue for rightward movement in wh- questions such as Aarons and Neidle, others, including Petronio and Lillo-Martin, have argued that ASL has leftward movement and wh- words that appear to the right of the clause move by other processes.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both analyses agree upon the fact that there is wh-movement present in these interrogative phrases, but it is a matter of what direction the wh-movement is moving in that causes controversy.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis is congruent with cross-linguistic data that wh-movement is always leftward.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It can be seen as the less controversial of the two proposals.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments presented by the Leftward Wh-movement analysis are: That the spec-CP is on the left, that the wh-movement is leftward, and that the final wh-word in a sentence is a base-generated double.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is illustrated in the syntax tree located to the right of this paragraph.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arguments for leftward movement are based on the facts that if wh-movement in ASL were rightward, ASL would be an exception to cross-linguistic generalizations that wh-movement is leftward.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has also been hypothesized that wh-elements cannot be topicalized, as topicalized elements must be presupposed and interrogatives are not.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This would be detrimental to the rightward analysis, as they are analyzing the doubled wh-word as a 'base generated topic'.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The rightward movement analysis is a newer, more abstract argument of how wh-movement occurs in ASL.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments for rightward movement begin by analyzing spec-CP as being on the right, the wh-movement as being rightward, and as the initial wh-word as a base-generated topic.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This can be seen in the syntax tree on the right.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] One of the rightward movement analysis' main arguments is in regards to the non-manual grammatical markings, and their optional spreading over the sentence.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL the use of non-manual grammatical markings is optional depending on the type of wh-question being asked.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the rightward analysis both partial and full spreading of non-manual grammatical markers can be accounted for due to the association with the +WH feature over its c-command domain.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the leftward analysis, the partial or full spreading of non manual grammatical markings cannot be accounted for in this same way.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis requires wh-marking to extend over the entirety of the question, regardless (which is not what is attested in ASL).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In spoken language Yes/no questions will oftentimes differ in their word order from the statement form.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL, yes/no questions are marked by the non-manual grammatical markings (as discussed in section 4.4.1).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This eyebrow raise, slight tilt of the head and lean forward are what indicate that a yes/no question is being asked, without any change in word order from the statement form.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is speculation amongst linguists that these non-manual grammatical markings that indicate a yes/no questions are similar to the question intonation of spoken languages.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Yes/no questions differ from wh-questions as they do not differ in word order from the original statement form of the sentence, whereas wh-questions do.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] As well, in yes/no questions, the non-manual marking must be used over the whole utterance in order for it to be judged as a statement opposed to a question.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The yes/no question is the same word order as the statement form of the sentence, with the addition of non-manual grammatical markings.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are also used for rhetorical questions, which are questions that do not intend to elicit an answer.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] To distinguish the non-manual marking for rhetorical questions from that of yes/no questions, the body is in a neutral position opposed to tilted forward, and the head is tilted in a different way than in yes/no questions.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rhetorical questions are much more common in ASL than in English.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] [I LIKE]NEGATIVE [WHAT?]RHETORICAL, GARLIC.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This strategy is commonly used instead of signing the word 'because' for clarity or emphasis.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] PASTA I EAT ENJOY TRUE [WHY?]RHETORICAL, ITALIAN I.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL signers set up regions of space (loci) for specific referents (see above); these can then be referred to indexically by pointing at those locations with pronouns and indexical verbs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, they point to their referent, or to a locus representing their referent.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the referent is not physically present, the speaker identifies the referent and then points to a location (the *locus)* in the sign space near their body.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This locus can then be pointed at to refer to the referent.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Theoretically, any number of loci may be set up, as long as the signer and recipient remember them all, but in practice, no more than eight loci are used.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier 1990 demonstrates that only two grammatical persons are distinguished in ASL: First person and non-first person, as in Damin.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both persons come in several numbers as well as with signs such as 'my' and 'by myself'.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier provides several arguments for believing that ASL does not formally distinguish second from third person.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, when pointing to a person that is physically present, a pronoun is equivalent to either 'you' or '(s)he' depending on the discourse.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is nothing in the sign itself, nor in the direction of eye gaze or body posture, that can be relied on to make this distinction.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, the same formal sign can refer to any of several second or third persons, which the indexic nature of the pronoun makes clear.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In English, indexic uses also occur, as in 'I need *you* to go to the store and *you* to stay here', but not so ubiquitously.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In contrast, several first-person ASL pronouns, such as the plural possessive ('our'), look different from their non-first-person equivalents, and a couple of pronouns do not occur in the first person at all, so first and non-first persons are formally distinct.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Personal pronouns have separate forms for singular ('I' and 'you/(s)he') and plural ('we' and 'you/they').
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These have possessive counterparts: 'my', 'our', 'your/his/her', 'your/their'.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, there are pronoun forms which incorporate numerals from two to five ('the three of us', 'the four of you/them', etc.), though the dual pronouns are slightly idiosyncratic in form *(i.e.,* they have a K rather than 2 handshape, and the wrist nods rather than circles).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These numeral-incorporated pronouns have no possessive equivalents.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Also among the personal pronouns are the 'self' forms ('by myself', 'by your/themselves', etc.).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These only occur in the singular and plural (there is no numeral incorporation), and are only found as subjects.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] They have derived emphatic and 'characterizing' forms, with modifications used for derivation rather like those for verbal aspect.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The 'characterizing' pronoun is used when describing someone who has just been mentioned.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] It only occurs as a non-first-person singular form.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Finally, there are formal pronouns used for honored guests.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These occur as singular and plural in the non-first person, but only as singular in the first person.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a pro-drop language, which means that pronouns are not used when the referent is obvious from context and is not being emphasized.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within ASL there is a class of indexical (often called 'directional') verbs.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These include the signs for 'see', 'pay', 'give', 'show', 'invite', 'help', 'send', 'bite', etc.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] These verbs include an element of motion that indexes one or more referents, either physically present or set up through the referent locus system.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] If there are two loci, the first indicates the subject and the second the object, direct or indirect depending on the verb, reflecting the basic word order of ASL.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'give' is a bi-indexical verb based on a flattened M/O handshape.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'I give you', the hand moves from myself toward you; for 'you give me', it moves from you to me.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] The verb 'to be in pain' (index fingers pointed at each other and alternately approaching and separating) is signed at the location of the pain (head for headache, cheek for toothache, abdomen for stomachache, etc.).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is normally done in relation to the signer's own body, regardless of the person feeling the pain, but may take also use the locus system, especially for body parts which are not normally part of the sign space, such as the leg.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are also spatial verbs such as put-up and put-below, which allow signers to specify where things are or how they moved them around.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-phabet] Like SignFont and Stokoe notation, ASL-phabet is a phonemic script, but it has been simplified to the point where there is some ambiguity, that is, one symbol can represent more than one phonemic element (handshape, location or movement).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-phabet] For example, whereas SignFont has 25 letters encoding types of movement, and Stokoe notation has 24, ASL-phabet has just 5.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-phabet] This can result in homographs (more than one sign spelled the same way).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-phabet] All together, ASL-phabet has 22 letters for handshape, 5 for location, and 5 for movement.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-phabet] They are written in that order, left-to-right, with the possibility for several letters of each type, such as two handshape letters for a two-handed sign.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-phabet] Like Stokoe notation (but unlike SignFont), the ASL-phabet does not provide symbols for facial expressions, mouthing, and other aspects of sign language structure, which may make it hard to use for extended text.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/asl-phabet] However, it is sufficient to look up ASL words in an ASL–English dictionary.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Its core components are digits, locatives, marks and movements which are written in a fairly rigid order (though in a fairly flexible configuration) from left to right.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The order of the writing is from left to right, top to bottom, with locatives or certain marks often beginning words.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Sentences are ended by the full stop mark ().
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Questions in written ASL are denoted by eyebrow marks bounding the question not unlike Spanish's "¿ ?." Question words or wh-questions in ASL can also form the interrogative.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] There are in total 105 characters in ASLwrite with 67 digits, five diacritic marks, twelve locatives, sixteen extramanual marks and five movement marks.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Since its creation, it has evolved to include more digits, locatives, movements and marks as well as modify those already present.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] si5s, a system built from SignWriting, was first proposed by Robert Arnold in his 2007 Gallaudet thesis *A Proposal of the Written System for ASL*.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The ASLwrite community split from Arnold upon his decision to maintain si5s as a private venture with ASLized after the publication of his and Adrean Clark's book *How to Write American Sign Language*.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Aside from the small, but dedicated, Facebook group of around 470 in July 2023, ASLwrite is rarely used outside such online spaces.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] However, one of the most popular online ASL dictionaries, HandSpeak, has begun to incorporate ASLwrite as the primary written component of ASL definitions.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] ASLwrite is a somacheirographic system meaning that it represents the body (Greek: σῶμα *sôma* 'body') and hands (Greek: χείρ *kheír* 'hand') and relays phonemic information.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] However, it also incorporates logographs (questioning marks) and is featural.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The general principle is to capture a single ASL word per segment, from left to right, registering non-manual feature(s), location(s), handshape(s), movement(s) and general orientation.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] It imagines the writer/speaker is looking down at their hands or viewing words from the profile such that words can be made either as if seen from straight-on or from one's profile.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet captures handshape information as well as orientation, movement and some locations.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Locatives are characters that capture location, though handshape diacritics like *edge* do capture some locations such as edge of palm.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Diacritics, such as movements, modify handshapes and can indicate small movements or small orientations.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements themselves are fairly flexible in their shapes and orientations, which makes digitising this script difficult.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Frontal or profile locatives – Captures the same location information, just from two perspectives.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] An example (seen on the right) is the shoulder locative is either a shoulder frontal locative that is written above or below the handshape(s).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Handshapes – Can be written before or after the locative.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] A handshape can be oriented in 360° depending on its location and is written at the end of its movement path if there is one.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Each handshape present is written, and when more than one handshape (of one hand) is written, a movement must be present.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements – Larger movements or movements that affect multiple handshapes.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] When a handshape changes without overt movement, the handshapes are written left-to-right with a single movement below, similar to an underline.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual & punctuation marks – These are questioning marks such as *why*, *who*, *how* and *how*.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet is composed of handshapes called digits that are modified by diacritics and movements.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] It shares 23 handshapes with ASL's manual alphabet.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Digits are grouped together by features such as +thumb/-thumb or +closed/-closed.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] In practise, there are 67 digits in ASLwrite's digibet, though that number is growing as new digits are added representing diverse handshapes.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Moreover, other languages may adopt this system which would add increasingly more digits.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] There are five diacritics, of which one is a movement diacritic.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Movements are flexible and thus hard to capture in a digital or non-handwritten fashion.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The movements are diverse and aim to capture the movements of the hands, arms and body.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] There are three points – an **endpoint**, a **firmpoint** and a **contactpoint** –, an **orbit mark**, a **steering** and a **crank mark** as well as the movement mark or line.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The movement line follows the path of the hand(s) and can be as clean (e.g., – or | ) or as erratic as possible.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The points denote the end of a handshape's path and the degree to which the motion is made.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] A contactpoint denotes an imaginary or in-the-air point with the contactpoint ending at a location and noted as being a firm ending with the firmpoint.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The orbit mark indicates a central "point" around which the handshapes orbit; for orbital paths cut short, one would use a steering mark, and for parallel cranking motions, the crank mark would be used.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The locatives are characters that denote a specific location on or near the signer's body.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] They are presented from a face-on and side-view.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The two sub-classifications are **frontal** and **profile locatives**.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual marks vary quite significantly and can only be placed at the beginning or end of words or phrases.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] **Eyebrow marks** are denoted before and after the word(s) in question thus bounding the words that are modified by eyebrow marks.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] They are called: **Raised (), Knit, Wan, Slanted** and **Squint**.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Questioning marks exist in ASL as logographs that denote ASL's wh-questions such as WHO or FOR-FOR.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] They are placed after a closed word's or phrase's second eyebrow mark and can exist as an entire sentence alone.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Mouth marks are characters that relay what action the mouth is doing.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] It is placed inside the first eyebrow mark.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Body movements are non-manual, non-facial features such as **shoulder shift ()** or **head nod**.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] They, as well as **nose crinkle ()**, stand alone and can be inserted anywhere, inside and outside of eyebrow-marked phrases.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] means *Yes?* in ASL composed of , , and where the raised eyebrow marks at the beginning and the end indicate it is a yes/no question, and the hinge mark () denotes that the S handshape digit () makes a nodding motion.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The circular point at the end is a full stop mark indicating the end of the sentence.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Unlike in English writing, the full stop mark () is employed for all sentences, even questions (as seen here).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Breaks in the sentence, as seen below, are denoted by the shoulder shift mark ().
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The text on the right is from Chapters 1:2–4 of the Book of Ruth.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] The first quoted text is the verse in English and the second is an ASL gloss.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] Due to the complexity of the writing system and its need for flexibility for movements, it means that producing anything in a digital format is difficult.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] However, there are efforts to create fonts headed by members of its Facebook group, notably looking at proper font creation and using current keyboard characters such as ' } ' or ' _.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] ' to achieve minor forms of communication in ASL over text.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/aslwrite] An example phrase is " }_.U- " which means 'thank you' in ASL.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/australian-irish-sign-language] From there and the establishment of three schools, AISL was used as a language of instruction until the early 1950s.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/australian-irish-sign-language] Prior to the 1875 arrival of ISL, British Sign Language (BSL) came to Australia in 1825 with the arrival of John Carmichael from Edinburgh.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/australian-irish-sign-language] The first schools for Deaf children were established in 1860 in both Sydney and Melbourne, however, the trajectory of BSL towards Auslan and that of ISL towards AISL differed.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/australian-irish-sign-language] Indeed, it was along the Protestant/Catholic line that the languages were taught, where Protestant schools taught BSL-later-Auslan, and Catholic schools taught ISL-later-AISL.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/australian-irish-sign-language] Both AISL and Auslan, however, stopped being used as languages of instruction after the disastrous Milan Congress of 1881, where by the 1950s, oralism cemented across Australia.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/australian-irish-sign-language] Since then, AISL has stopped being used in Deaf clubs or wider community settings, now only being used by small friend groups from the now-closed schools and between family members.
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/australian-irish-sign-language] Although Australia has a National Policy on Language, it only mentions Auslan (not even Australian Aboriginal sign languages).
[src:australian-irish-sign-language/australian-irish-sign-language] As of 2017, there were not teachers, professionals, nor interpreters who are able to provide services in AISL.
